Critical Base Implementations

To achieve a "well-made" design, focus your implementation effort on these four pillars.
Everything else belongs in user space.

1. High-Performance IPC

The kernel must implement synchronous rendezvous-based IPC. When Process A sends a 
message to Process B, A blocks until B receives and replies.

    Optimization: Use CPU registers to pass small messages (up to 3-4 words) without 
    touching memory. This reduces IPC latency to nanoseconds.

    Design Choice: Do not buffer messages in the kernel. If the receiver is not ready,
    the sender sleeps. This simplifies kernel memory management. 

2. Capability-Based Access Control

Replace traditional UID/GID or global file descriptors with capabilities.

    Every thread has a Capability Table (CTable).
    To access a resource (e.g., a hardware port or another thread), a process must 
    hold a capability in its CTable.
    IPC Transfer: Capabilities can be attached to IPC messages, allowing processes to 
    securely delegate access rights to others (e.g., init granting a driver access to 
    a specific memory region). 

3. External Memory Management

The kernel should only manage physical frames. It must not implement page replacement
algorithms or swap logic.

    Page Faults: When a process accesses an unmapped address, the hardware traps to 
    the kernel. The kernel suspends the thread and sends an IPC message to the VM Server.
    Policy: The VM Server decides whether to kill the process, map a new zero-page,
    or load data from disk. It then instructs the kernel to map the physical frame.

4. Bootstrapping and Init

The kernel's main.c should do the absolute minimum:

    Initialize hardware (MMU, Interrupts).
    Create the root capability space.
    Load the Init Server from the rootfs into memory.
    Jump to the Init Server's entry point.
    From this point on, the kernel is idle until an IPC call or interrupt occurs. 
    The Init Server spawns the Process Manager, Filesystem, and Drivers. 

Summary of Responsibilities

Component	        Location	Responsibility
Thread Switching	Kernel	    Save/Restore registers, schedule next thread.
Address Spaces	    Kernel	    Map virtual to physical (on request), TLB maintenance.
IPC	                Kernel	    Copy message registers, switch address spaces, block/unblock threads.
Interrupts	        Kernel	    Identify source, forward as IPC message to registered Driver Thread.
File Systems	    Userspace	Parse inodes, manage directories, talk to block drivers via IPC.
Networking	        Userspace	TCP/IP stack, packet routing via IPC with NIC driver.
Memory Policy	    Userspace	Decide what to page out, handle malloc/free logic. 

By strictly limiting the kernel/ directory to these mechanisms and pushing all logic to servers/ and drivers/, 
you achieve a system that is secure by design, easy to debug, and truly "suckless." 

HARDWARE ABSTRACTION LAYER

Designing a Hardware Abstraction Layer (HAL) for a Suckless Microkernel

For a suckless microkernel, the HAL must be minimal, static, and compile-time bound. Unlike monolithic kernels 
(Linux) or heavy RTOSs, you do not need dynamic driver loading or complex runtime polymorphism. The goal is to 
isolate architecture-specific register manipulation behind a clean interface so the kernel/ logic remains portable.

Core Design Principles

    Static Binding (No Vtables): Avoid runtime overhead (vtables, function pointers) for basic operations. 
    Use static inline functions or compile-time selection (#ifdef) to resolve hardware calls. This ensures 
    zero overhead compared to direct register access.
    Struct-Based Register Maps: Represent hardware peripherals as volatile C structs mapped to base addresses. 
    This provides type safety and readability without external libraries.
    Thin Wrappers Only: The HAL should only expose mechanism (e.g., uart_putc(char)), not policy (e.g., printf). 
    Higher-level logic belongs in lib/ or servers/.
    Header-Only Implementation: For maximum performance and inlining, implement the HAL primarily in header files. 
    This allows the compiler to optimize away the abstraction layer entirely. 

