Integration with Kernel

The kernel main.c never includes architecture-specific headers directly. It relies solely on hal.h.

/* kernel/main.c */
#include <hal.h>

void kernel_main(void) {
    hal_uart_init(); // Calls arch-specific init
    hal_console_putc('B'); 
    hal_console_putc('o');
    hal_console_putc('o');
    hal_console_putc('t');
    
    // Architecture agnostic logic
    while(1) {
        hal_irq_enable();
        __asm__ volatile("hlt"); // or "wfi" on ARM
    }
}
 

This design ensures that adding a new architecture (e.g., RISC-V) only requires creating arch/riscv64/hal/ 
with matching function names. The kernel/ code remains untouched, preserving the mechanism vs. policy 
separation essential for a microkernel.

INTER-PROCESS CALLS

Design Proposal: Synchronous Rendezvous with Capability Transfer

Based on the proven designs of L4 and seL4, here is a minimal, 
high-performance IPC mechanism tailored for microkernels.

Core Philosophy

    Synchronous Rendezvous: No kernel buffering. 
    The sender blocks until the receiver is ready.
    This eliminates memory allocation in the kernel and prevents 
    DoS attacks via message flooding.

    Register-Based Passing: Small messages (up to 3 machine words)
    are passed directly in CPU registers during the context switch,
    achieving zero-copy for the common case.

    Capability Transfer: Access rights (capabilities) can be attached
    to messages, allowing secure delegation of resources (e.g., a file
    descriptor or memory region) between processes.

    Direct Process Switch: When Thread A sends to Thread B, the kernel
    switches directly from A to B, donating A's remaining time slice to B.
    This avoids scheduler overhead. 

1. Message Structure

The message is split into fast path (registers) and slow path (memory buffer).
Component	Size	    Location	            Description
Label	    1 word	    Register arg0	        Message type / function ID (e.g., READ, WRITE).
Data	    2 words	    Registers arg1, arg2	Inline arguments (e.g., offset, length, status code).
Capability	1 word	    Register arg3	        Optional capability index to transfer (e.g., FD, Memory Cap).
Buffer	    Variable	Memory (User Space)	    For large payloads. Sender/receiver must agree on a pre-mapped 
                                                shared buffer address passed via registers.

Design Decision: Do not support arbitrary-sized messages in the kernel. If a process needs to send >12 bytes 
(on 64-bit), it must map a shared memory region via a capability and send the address and capability 
in the registers.

2. System Call Interface

Expose only two system calls to user space. Complexity is pushed to user-space libraries.
ipc_send_recv(dest_thread_id, msg, timeout)

    Action: Sends msg to dest_thread_id and atomically waits for a reply.
    Behavior:

        Validates dest_thread_id capability.
        If receiver is waiting (ipc_wait), performs immediate context switch (Direct Switch).
        If receiver is not waiting, blocks sender on the destination's endpoint queue.
        Returns the reply message in the same register structure.

    Timeout: Prevents permanent deadlocks. 0 = non-blocking (fail immediately), -1 = infinite. 

ipc_wait(source_thread_id, timeout)

    Action: Waits for a message from source_thread_id (or ANY if wildcarded).
    Behavior:

        Marks thread as "waiting for IPC".
        If a sender is already blocked on this thread, performs immediate context switch to the sender.
        Otherwise, blocks until a message arrives or timeout. 

seL4 system call IPC send recv implementation
3. Capability Transfer Mechanism

To send a resource (e.g., a memory page) to another process:

    Sender: Holds a capability in its CTable at index X.
    Send: Places X in the arg3 (Capability) register and sets a "HasCap" flag in the Label.
    Kernel Action:

        Validates Sender has "Grant" right on X.
        Validates Receiver has "Receive" right on the endpoint.
        Moves (or copies, depending on policy) the capability from Sender's CTable to 
            Receiver's CTable (at a slot specified by Receiver or a default inbox).
        Clears the slot in Sender's table (move semantics).

    Receiver: Gets the new capability index in the reply, allowing it to access the resource. 

4. Kernel Data Structures

Keep these minimal in kernel/ipc.c and include/ipc.h.
struct endpoint

Represents a communication channel.

struct endpoint {
    lock_t lock;
    struct thread *waiting_sender; // Queue head
    struct thread *waiting_receiver; // Queue head
    // No message buffer!
};
 
struct thread (Extensions)

struct thread {
    // ... existing fields ...
    struct endpoint *ipc_endpoint; // Endpoint this thread is waiting on
    struct message_regs ipc_msg;   // Saved registers during IPC
    struct capability *ipc_cap;    // Capability being transferred
};
 
5. Execution Flow (The "Happy Path")

This scenario describes a Client requesting data from a Server with zero scheduler invocation.

    Client executes ipc_send_recv(ServerID, msg).
    Kernel looks up ServerID. Finds Server is already waiting in ipc_wait().
    Kernel locks the Endpoint.
    Kernel copies registers arg0-arg3 from Client's trap frame to Server's trap frame.
    Kernel switches the page directory (Address Space) from Client to Server.
    Kernel restores registers and jumps to Server's instruction pointer.
    Server resumes inside ipc_wait(), returning the received message.
    (Server processes request)
    Server executes ipc_send_recv(ClientID, reply) (using the "Reply Capability" left by Client).
    Kernel sees Client is waiting. Repeats steps 4-6 in reverse.
    Client resumes inside ipc_send_recv(), receiving the reply.

Total Overhead: 2 Trap entries + 2 Context Switches. 
No memory copies, no queue management, no scheduler run-queue traversal.

6. Handling Large Data (Zero-Copy Shared Memory)

For payloads >3 words (e.g., file data, network packets):

    Setup: Client and Server share a memory region. This is done by a previous IPC where a Memory Capability was transferred.
    Request: Client sends ipc_send_recv with Label=READ, arg1=offset, arg2=buffer_addr.
    Transfer: Server writes data directly to buffer_addr (which is mapped in both address spaces).
    Reply: Server replies with Label=OK, arg1=bytes_written.

The kernel never touches the large payload; it only manages the capabilities that allow the mapping.

